					<description><![CDATA[I&#039;ve been reading a lot of articles about writing habits and routines for the last four years or so and this is the one that has helped me most. Great idea to take the ideas of worthy writers and compile them to find out the consistent habits. I have adopted the 7-12 every morning approach and finding I have to compensate with a lot of exercise by necessity. Excellent post and thank you. You have done wonders for the quality of my output.

P.S. ^Regarding the Jericho Rivers idea, I can only say that I&#039;ve never heard of you, but if you are &quot;successful&quot; as you say and happy with your work then great, I envy you. But what you&#039;re saying is crap. Even the most spontaneous and enthusiastic writers like Ray Bradbury worked out a routine naturally. There are a few spontaneous novel writer&#039;s that have been worthy out there, but they are very, very much the minority. Your ideas might work for poetry and maybe for you if you really are &quot;successful&quot;, but your talk of &quot;fleshing&quot; and so on makes me think you&#039;re more concerned with looking successful and making money than integrity of fiction.

In the words of Jack London:- &#039;You can&#039;t wait for inspiration. You have to go after it with a club.&#039;]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve been reading a lot of articles about writing habits and routines for the last four years or so and this is the one that has helped me most. Great idea to take the ideas of worthy writers and compile them to find out the consistent habits. I have adopted the 7-12 every morning approach and finding I have to compensate with a lot of exercise by necessity. Excellent post and thank you. You have done wonders for the quality of my output.</p>
<p>P.S. ^Regarding the Jericho Rivers idea, I can only say that I&#8217;ve never heard of you, but if you are &#8220;successful&#8221; as you say and happy with your work then great, I envy you. But what you&#8217;re saying is crap. Even the most spontaneous and enthusiastic writers like Ray Bradbury worked out a routine naturally. There are a few spontaneous novel writer&#8217;s that have been worthy out there, but they are very, very much the minority. Your ideas might work for poetry and maybe for you if you really are &#8220;successful&#8221;, but your talk of &#8220;fleshing&#8221; and so on makes me think you&#8217;re more concerned with looking successful and making money than integrity of fiction.</p>
<p>In the words of Jack London:- &#8216;You can&#8217;t wait for inspiration. You have to go after it with a club.&#8217;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
